rratives and traditions and at the same time constructed them as representative of Hawaiian culture. Hawaiian mo'olelo were translated in popular and scholarly English-language publications to market a new cultural product: a space constructed primarily for Euro-Americans as something simultaneously exotic and primitive and beautiful and welcoming. To analyze this representation of Hawaiian traditions, place, and genre, Bacchilega focuses on translation across languages, cultures, and media; on photography, as the technology that contributed to the visual formation of a westernized image of Hawai'i; and on tourism as determining postannexation economic and ideological machinery.In a book with interdisciplinary appeal, Bacchilega demonstrates both how the myth of legendary Hawai'i emerged and how this vision can be unmade and reimagined.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFolk literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aHawaiiansxFolklore. 0aLegendszHawaiixHistory and criticism. 0aOral traditionzHawaiixHistory and criticism. 4aLiterature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Folklore & Mythology.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aCultural Studies.  aFolklore.  aLinguistics.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Social Sciencesz978311041361808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220117840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812201178423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812201178/original  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041361-8  Penn Press eBook Package Social Sciences  a978-3-11-0